at|^b@2^z@3|
cs|5|cp|6|fp|4|
at||fp||cp||at|
This chapter is all about competitive bidding, but most of what you have learned so far has been about how the partnership that opened the bidding can deal with interference (in the form of a takeout double or an overcall) from the opponents. It is time to give the other partnership (the one that did not open the bidding) some new tools to help them with their decisions in competitive auctions.

|
qx|5.3|
pg| ***** 0 ***** |


at|In the early days of bridge, there were 2 bids available that could be used to show very strong hands after an opening bid by the opponents:

|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2s|at| }

|
pg| ***** 1 ***** |


at|In the first auction, South jumps to 2NT after East's opening bid (which is 1@H in this example). Traditionally, this 2NT overcall was used to describe a hand that would have opened the bidding with 2NT.

|
pg| ***** 2 ***** |


at|In the second auction, South cuebids the suit that East opened (spades in this case). When bridge was a new game, a direct cuebid of the suit that was opened by an opponent was used to describe a hand that would have opened the bidding with a strong 2-bid (that is, a hand rich in high cards that was strong enough to make a game contract all on its own).

|
pg| ***** 3 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2s|at| }

Nowadays most bidding systems (including SAYC) do not use the 2NT overcall or the direct cuebid of the opener's suit to show strong hands. Modern bridge players have come to realize that the traditional meanings of these bids are not very useful. There are 2 reasons for this:

|
pg| ***** 4 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ It is very rare to be dealt a hand strong enough for a 2NT opening or a 
 strong 2-bid when one of the opponents has opened the bidding. }

|
pg| ***** 5 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ If you are dealt such a strong hand and hear an opponent open the bidding in front 
 of you, there are other ways in which you can describe your hand to your partner. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 6 ***** |


at|Specifically, you can start by making a takeout double. At your next turn you can bid notrump, jump in notrump, bid a new suit, jump in a new suit, or cuebid the opener's suit. These followups can be used by a player who made a takeout double to describe various types of strong hands. These auctions were described in detail in the original Learn to Play Bridge program.

So it makes sense to assign new meanings to the 2NT overcall and the direct cuebid after an opponent opens the bidding at the 1-level. There are no universally accepted meanings for these bids. The way in which these bids are used in the SAYC bidding system is certainly as popular and arguably as effective as any of the alternatives that have been devised so far.

|
pg| ***** 7 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1c!2n|at| }

|cs|3|at|^-{ A jump to 2NT after an opponent's 1-level opening bid describes a hand with at least 
 5-5 in the 2 lowest ranking unbid suits. This convention is called the Unusual notrump. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 8 ***** |


at|In the first example auction, South's 2NT overcall would show at least 5-5 in the minors (since clubs and diamonds are the 2 lowest ranking unbid suits). In the second example auction, the lowest ranking unbid suits are diamonds and hearts and South's 2NT would show at least 5-5 in those 2 suits. We will consider the strength promised by the Unusual notrump soon.

|
pg| ***** 9 ***** |


cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1d!2d|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2s|at| }

|cs|2|at|^-{ A direct cuebid of an opponent's minor suit opening bid 
 describes a hand with at least 5-5 in the major suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 10 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ A direct cuebid of an opponent's major suit opening bid describes a hand with 
 at least 5 cards in the unbid major and at least 5 cards in one of the minors. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 11 ***** |


at|In the first example, South's 2@D cuebid promises at least 5 hearts and at least 5 spades. In the second auction, South's 2@S cuebid shows at least 5 hearts and at least 5 cards in either diamonds or clubs. In both cases, this convention is known as the Michaels cuebid.
|
pg| ***** 12 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
|cs|2|at|^B{ Historical note} |cs|1|at|^G{ @2The Unusual notrump convention was devised in 1948 by Alvin Roth @3
of New York City (the same person who helped to develop the negative double). The Michaels cuebid was invented in the early 1960s by Michael Michaels of Miami Beach, a close associate of Charles Goren. } ^b@2^z@3^^|
pg| ***** 13 ***** |


at|
The next question to explore is how strong your hand should be in order to make an Unusual 2NT overcall or a Michaels cuebid. As we will see, this is not a simple question to answer, but here is a rough guideline that you can use

|
pg| ***** 14 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In most cases, 10 or more total points are required to use one of these conventions, but a 
 Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening bid can be made with as few as 8 total points. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 15 ***** |


n#|8|cs|1|at|^^^B{ |ia|  1c!2cp?|at| }    @2
|ht|m|at|Why is it that a Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening bid can be made with only 8 total points while at least 10 total points are required in all other cases? Consider what happens ^*Iafter^*N one of these conventions is used.
^b@2^z@3
|
pg| ***** 16 ***** |


cs|2|at|^^^-{ When responding to one of these conventions, you should bid one of your partner's suits. 
 Bid your longer of these suits and bid the lower ranking of these suits if you have equal length. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


at|^^In the case of the auction shown above, the partner of the player who bids Michaels can bid at the 2-level. In all other Michaels and Unusual 2NT auctions, the partner of the player who uses one of these conventions might have to go to the 3-level to bid one of his partner's long suits.

|
pg| ***** 18 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|When an Unusual 2NT overcall is used, the partner of the player who made that bid always knows exactly which 2 long suits have been shown. The same is true when a Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening has been made. 

|
pg| ***** 19 ***** |


at|After a Michaels cuebid of a major suit opening, things are different. The partner of the player who makes such a bid knows only one of the long suits that have been shown (the unbid major). He knows that his partner has at least 5 cards in one of the minor suits as well, but how does he find out if that suit is clubs or diamonds?

|ht|k|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2hp?|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2sp?|at| }

|
pg| ***** 20 ***** |


n#|3|cs|2|at|^-{ Bid 2NT in response to a Michaels cuebid of a major suit 
 opening bid to ask your partner to bid his long minor suit. }
^-
|ht|k|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h2hp!2np?|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s2sp!2np?|at| }
|
pg| ***** 21 ***** |


ht|t|at|In both of the above auctions, the 2NT bid asks South to bid 3@C if his other 5-card suit is clubs and to bid 3@D if his other 5-card suit is diamonds. Since the Michaels cuebid could be based on a very strong hand, South can bid something else (jumping to 4@C or 4@D for example), but most of the time he will simply bid his long minor suit at the 3-level.

|
pg| ***** 22 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ The Michaels cuebid and the Unusual notrump have no upper limit in terms of strength. }

|
pg| ***** 23 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|At|Let's return to the question of which types of hands are appropriate for a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual notrump overcall. As we have seen, at least 10 total points are required to use these conventions in most cases, but 8 total points is enough for a Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening bid. Furthermore, these conventions should not be used without at least 5 cards in 2 suits. Some bridge players make the mistake of using these conventions on occasion with 5-4 (or 6-4) in their 2 long suits. Don't be one of them!

|
pg| ***** 24 ***** |


at|Another mistake that some bridge players make is to use these conventions whenever they have the appropriate strength and distribution to do so. Deciding whether or not a Michaels cuebid or Unusual 2NT overcall should be used on a given hand that meets the requirements is a matter of judgment. We will explore several factors that should be considered:

|
pg| ***** 25 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ If most of your high cards are in your long suits, your hand is more suitable for these bids. 
 If most of your high cards are in your short suits, you should consider some other action. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 26 ***** |


at|^^For example, both of the hands shown below have the same distribution and the same number of high card points,  but the first hand is more appropriate for an Unusual 2NT overcall of a major suit opening bid than the second hand. The reason is that the first hand has most of its strength in its long suits while the second hand has most of its strength in its short suits.

|n#|8|cs|3|ht|r|at|^D{|ih|ps3h76daj754ckqt86|at|} |ht|r|at|^P{|ih|pssahkqdj7543ct8654|at|} 

|
pg| ***** 27 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
The vulnerability plays a key role is deciding whether or not you should make a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall when you have a borderline hand for these actions:

|
pg| ***** 28 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ If you are vulnerable you should be less aggressive in using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 29 ***** |


at|It is a fact of life that sometimes your partner will not have a fit for either one of your suits when you use a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall. When this happens, the opponents may double whatever contract you play in. If you are not vulnerable, the size of the penalty that they collect will be less!

|
pg| ***** 30 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{If the opponents are vulnerable you should be more aggressive in using these conventions.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 31 ***** |


at|Getting doubled in a contract that fails is not always a disaster. If the opponents can make a game or slam contract of their own, it is ok to let them collect a penalty instead by doubling your contract (assuming the penalty is not too big). If this is the case you will be taking a sacrifice. 

If the opponents are vulnerable they will collect more bonus points for bidding and making a game or slam contract than they will collect if they are not vulnerable. As a result, you can afford to fail by more tricks in a doubled contract when the opponents are vulnerable.

|
pg| ***** 32 ***** |


ht|r|n#|8|at|There are 4 possible vulnerabilities in bridge. You should be most aggressive in using conventions like the Michaels cuebid and the Unusual notrump when only the opponents are vulnerable. Be a little more careful when neither side is vulnerable, considerably more careful when both sides are vulnerable, and extremely careful when only your side is vulnerable!

|
pg| ***** 33 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|For example, here is a borderline hand for an Unusual 2NT overcall after a 1@S opening bid:

|ht|c|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps8h63dkqt96cqjt84|at|} |ht|d|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1s?|at| }


|
pg| ***** 34 ***** |


n#|5|at|This hand has 8 HCP |
pg| ***** 35 ***** |


at|and 2 long suit points (1 for each of the 5-card minors). With 10 total points, this hand is just strong enough to consider making an Unusual 2NT overcall. Whether or not such a bid should be made is largely a matter of judgment and the vulnerability should be one of the factors that you should consider when you are faced with this decision.

|
pg| ***** 36 ***** |


at|If only the opponents were vulnerable it would be a good time to bid 2NT. Your partnership may not end up buying the contract. If your side does buy the contract, you may get doubled and fail by several tricks. Still, this vulnerability favors sacrificing since the bonus points that the opponents score for succeeding in a game or slam is greater when they are vulnerable and the bonus points they score for collecting doubled undertricks is smaller when you are not vulnerable.
|ht|d|cs|1|sv|e|fa|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1s!2n|at| }
|
pg| ***** 37 ***** |


ht|d|cs|1|sv|n|fa|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1s!p|at| }
|ht|q|n#|9|at|If only your side was vulnerable then the tables would be turned. Now you should pass since the opponents would collect a bigger penalty if they doubled you and they would collect fewer bonus points if they succeeded in a game or slam contract.

|
pg| ***** 38 ***** |


ht|u|at|If neither side was vulnerable or both sides were vulnerable the decision would be closer. What call should South make under these circumstances? That is really a matter of judgment!|
ht|d|cs|1|sv|e|fa||at|^N{ |ia|  1s!?|at| }
|
pg| ***** 39 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
Here is another important factor to consider in deciding whether or not to make a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall:

|
pg| ***** 40 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Having strong spot cards in your long suits is a plus factor for using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 41 ***** |


at|For example, let's take another look at the problem we just saw. It was stated that whether or not South should overcall 2NT with this hand is a close decision when neither side is vulnerable:

|ht|j|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|ps8h63dkqt96cqjt84|at|} |ht|k|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1s?|at| }


|
pg| ***** 42 ***** |


n#|5|at|Notice that this hand has some excellent spot cards in its long suits. The @D10, @D9, @C10, and @C8 all help to make this hand strong in terms of its potential to win tricks with one of the minor suits as trump.

|
pg| ***** 43 ***** |


cs|3|at|^^^^^C{|ih|ps8h63dkq653cqj542|at|}     @2
|ht|s|n#|2|at|If the beautiful spot cards in the above hand were replaced by the horrible spot cards in this hand, the decision is much less close. This is still a question of judgment, but the judgment of this author is that South should pass over 1@S with this hand due to its poor spot cards in the minors.|
pg| ***** 44 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|Have you had enough yet? Hopefully you are still willing to listen to some more considerations that should come into play when deciding whether or not to use one of these 2-suited overcalls:

|
pg| ***** 45 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ A serious disparity in the quality of your 2 suits is a minus factor for using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 46 ***** |


ht|f|n#|5|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psaqj86ht9742dk6ct|at|} |ht|g|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1d?|at| }


|
pg| ***** 47 ***** |


n#|5|at|This hand is certainly strong enough for a Michaels cuebid of 2@D and, with 5 spades and 5 hearts, it has the correct distribution. |
pg| ***** 48 ***** |


at|However, there are 2 reasons why a 1@S overcall might work out better in practice and both of these reasons have to do with the fact that the spade suit is much stronger than the heart suit in this hand. |
ht|g|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1d!1s|at| }
|
pg| ***** 49 ***** |


ht|p|at|First, if South used Michaels and North was dealt the same number of cards in hearts and spades, he should bid his hearts (because hearts is the lower ranking of the 2 suits that South would be showing). South's hearts are weak |
pg| ***** 50 ***** |


at|and his spades are strong. If North has the same number of cards in the majors, it is likely that more tricks will be available if spades are trump.

|
pg| ***** 51 ***** |


at|Second, if the opponents end up playing the contract and North is to be the opening leader, South has a strong preference for a spade opening lead. If South overcalls 1@S, then his partner is likely to lead that suit. If South uses a Michaels cuebid, his partner will not know which of the majors he should lead. |
pg| ***** 52 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|psaqj86ht9742dk6ct|at|} |ht|c|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1d!1s|at| }


|n#|5|At|One of the nice things about overcalling 1@S with this hand |
pg| ***** 53 ***** |


at|(as opposed to using a Michaels cuebid to show both majors) |
pg| ***** 54 ***** |


at|is that South can later bid his hearts if it seems like a good idea to do so. Things would be different if South's major suits were reversed:

|
pg| ***** 55 ***** |


ht|l|n#|5|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|phaqj86st9742dk6ct|at|} |ht|m|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1d?|at| }


|
pg| ***** 56 ***** |


n#|5|At|Now South's hearts are much stronger |
pg| ***** 57 ***** |


at|than his spades |
pg| ***** 58 ***** |


at|and that suggests that a 1@H overcall might work better |
pg| ***** 59 ***** |


at|than a Michaels cuebid of 2@D. The problem with this action is that if South overcalls 1@H and later bids spades, North will think that South's hearts are longer than his spades (since a player would normally overcall in the higher ranking of 2 5-card suits). 

|
pg| ***** 60 ***** |


at|Again, this is a judgment situation, but the judgment of the author of this program is that a Michaels cuebid of 2@D is the correct bid with this hand even though a 1@S overcall was recommended with the very similar hand shown at the top of this page.

|ht|m|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1d!2d|at| }

|
pg| ***** 61 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
|cs|1|at|^^^B{ |ia|  1d!1S|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1d!2d|at| }

|cs|3|at|^^^C   {|ih|psaqj86ht9742dk6ct|at|} |n#|t|at|^p   { |ih|phaqj86st9742dk6ct|at|} 
So a 1@S overcall is the recommended bid with the first hand and a Michaels cuebid of 2@D is the recommended bid with the second hand. There is an important lesson to be learned from this:

|
pg| ***** 62 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ In deciding between making an overcall and using Michaels or the Unusual notrump, 
 consider the implications of the overcall as far as your second 5-card suit is concerned. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 63 ***** |


at|With the first hand, the 1@S overcall has a lot to recommend to it because South may still get a chance to show his (weaker) heart suit later in the auction. |
pg| ***** 64 ***** |


at|^^^^With the second hand, there is no point in overcalling 1@S since the spades |
pg| ***** 65 ***** |


at|are so much weaker than the hearts. A 1@H overcall is unappetizing for a different reason: if South overcalls 1@H he will never be able to show his spade suit at all.

Michaels gives the partnership a chance to play in either suit and North will bid hearts if he has equal length in the majors.

|
pg| ***** 66 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Knowing that your partner will bid the lower ranking suit with equal length can be helpful! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 67 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|So far all of the example hands that we have looked at have contained exactly 5-5 in the 2 long suits. Some special considerations arise when the hand in question has at least 6-5 in the 2 suits:

|
pg| ***** 68 ***** |


cs|4|At|^-{ The more distribution you have, the more you should strive to bid something! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 69 ***** |


at|This should not come as a surprise to you. For one thing, a hand with 6-5 distribution has 1 more long suit point than a similar hand with 5-5 distribution. More important, the more distributional a hand is, the more tricks it is likely to win on offense and the less tricks it is likely to win on defense. That is a very good reason to get involved in the bidding (as opposed to passing)!

|
pg| ***** 70 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Some hands with unequal length in the long suits should overcall instead of using Michaels 
 or the Unusual notrump as these conventions could lead to a contract in the wrong suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 71 ***** |


at|Here is an example of this principle at work:

|ht|n|n#|5|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pskqjt62h8djcaq653|at|} |ht|o|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1h?|at| }


|
pg| ***** 72 ***** |


n#|5|at|This hand has the necessary distribution and strength for a Michaels cuebid (to show spades and one of the minors in this case), |
pg| ***** 73 ***** |


at|but there is a lot of be said for the alternative of a 1@S overcall. Can you see how a 1@S overcall might work out better than a Michaels cuebid of 2@D when South has this hand?
|ht|o|n#|5|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1h!1s|at| }
|
pg| ***** 74 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C{|ih|pskqjt62h8djcaq653|at|} |ht|c|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1h!2hp?|at| }

|n#|5|at|The advantage of using a Michaels cuebid with this hand is that this bid tells your partner that you have a 2-suiter. |
pg| ***** 75 ***** |


at|
Furthermore, bidding 2@H as Michaels increases your chances of playing in a contract with clubs as trump when that is right. Unfortunately, a Michaels cuebid also increases your chances of playing clubs when that is wrong. Perhaps North has some non-descript hand like the following:
|
pg| ***** 76 ***** |


n#|5|cs|3|at|^^^^^C{|ih|ps95hqt93dt976ckt4|at| }     @2
|ht|m|at|This hand has only 2 cards in spades and North has no way of knowing that you have a 6-card spade suit. North will not bid 2@S if he has a hand like this one. |
pg| ***** 77 ***** |


at|He will bid 2NT to ask you to bid your long minor in order to ensure that the partnership plays in at least an 8-card trump fit.
^b@2
|ht|c|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1h2hp!2np?|at| }

|
pg| ***** 78 ***** |


ht|c|cs|1|at|^N{ |ia|  1h2hp2np!3c|at| }
|ht|s|n#|5|at|^b@2Playing in 3@C does not rate to be the end of the world. If clubs are trump, 10 tricks will be available with a little bit of luck. |
pg| ***** 79 ***** |


at|^^^^The bad news is that it takes even less luck for North-South to win 10 tricks in spades and that is enough to succeed in the game contract of 4@S. It is the case that North-South may not be able to bid to 4@S after a 1@S overcall. Still, this example does illustrate the danger of using a Michaels cuebid on a hand like South's.|
pg| ***** 80 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
We have now seen several factors that a player should use to decide between using a Michaels cuebid or Unusual 2NT overcall to describe a 2-suited hand with a single bid (compared to passing or overcalling in a long suit):

|
pg| ***** 81 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ If most of your high cards are in your long suits, your hand is more suitable for these bids. 
 If most of your high cards are in your short suits, you should consider some other action. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 82 ***** |


