nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|Now please don't try to memorize the entire list that was presented on the previous page! If you consciously try to consider all of these factors every time you have a hand that might be suitable for a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall, not only will you probably get overwhelmed by all of the things you have to consider, but the bridge games that you play in will slow down to a snail's pace as a result!

So how is a bridge player supposed to weigh all of these considerations when he is faced with a bidding decision like the ones we have been considering? You probably guessed the answer - he has to rely on his judgment. Judgment is that mysterious thing that comes from experience. The more times you are faced with a particular type of hand in a particular type of auction, the better your chances will be to come up with the winning decision the next time you face such a problem.

It does help to keep in mind the reason why conventions like the Michaels cuebid and the Unusual notrump should be used in the first place:
