at|The first advantage shown above speaks for itself. The more your partner knows about your hand, the better the decisions that he will be able to make in the bidding (and on defense if one of the opponents ends up as declarer).

|
pg| ***** 98 ***** |


at|In terms of the second advantage, can you think of why "later" may never come for your second suit if you overcall instead of using one of the conventions that we have been studying?

|
pg| ***** 99 ***** |


at|There are a couple of ways that this might happen. First, it is possible that all 3 players will pass after you overcall. If this happens, you may well find yourself in an inferior trump fit. Second, the opponents might do some more bidding and the auction may be at a level too high for you to comfortably show your second suit when your next turn to bid comes along.

|
