nt|^b@2^z@3
There are also 2 main disadvantages to Michaels cuebids and Unusual notrump overcalls:

|
pg| ***** 101 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. These conventions force your partner to bid one of your long suits at a fairly high 
 level. Sometimes your partner will not have a good fit for either one of your suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 102 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{2. These conventions tell your opponents a lot about the nature of your hand in a single bid.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 103 ***** |


at|When the first disadvantage shown above rears its ugly head, your partnership may find itself doubled in an unhappy contract. Furthermore, on some of these deals, a simple overcall of one of your long suits would have kept your partnership out of danger (an overcall will usually come at a lower level than a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall).

Don't be too frightened about the first disadvantage displayed above. If you use good judgment in terms of when you invoke these conventions, you will not suffer very many serious penalties and those that you do give up will often represent good sacrifices.

|
pg| ***** 104 ***** |


at|There are several ways in which the second disadvantage can bite you. If one of the opponents ends up as the declarer, it may make it easier for him to play the hand if he knows that you have at least 5-5 distribution. Similarly, if you end up as the declarer, the defenders will have an easier time figuring out the contents of the unseen hands if they know that you have at least 5-5 distribution. Finally, these conventions sometimes help your opponents make accurate decisions in the bidding. On some deals, for example, a Michaels cuebid or Unusual 2NT overcall will warn your opponents that suits may not be breaking very well.

|
