|cp||at|The purpose of this topic was to introduce 2 conventions that are used in the SAYC bidding system to help your partnership with its competitive bidding after an opponent's 1-level opening bid. 

These conventions are called the Unusual notrump and the Michaels cuebid and they are used in auctions like the following:

|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2s|at| }

|
pg| ***** 156 ***** |


at|In the early days of bridge, the 2NT jump overcall was used to show a hand that would have opened the bidding 2NT. The direct cuebid of the opener's suit (2@S in the auction on the right) was used to show a hand that would have opened with a strong 2-bid. There are 2 reasons why modern bidding theorists disagreed with the traditional meanings assigned to these bids:

|
pg| ***** 157 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ It is very rare to be dealt a hand strong enough for a 2NT opening or a 
 strong 2-bid when one of the opponents has opened the bidding. }

|
pg| ***** 158 ***** |


cs|4|at|{ If you are dealt such a strong hand and hear an opponent open the bidding in front 
 of you, there are other ways in which you can describe your hand to your partner. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 159 ***** |


tb||

nt|^b@2^z@3
Here is a reminder of how the Unusual 2NT overcall works:

|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1c!2n|at| }

|cs|3|at|^-{ A jump to 2NT after an opponent's 1-level opening bid describes a hand with at least 
 5-5 in the 2 lowest ranking unbid suits. This convention is called the Unusual notrump. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 160 ***** |


at|Note that unbid is a key word in this definition. The 2NT bid in the first auction shows clubs and diamonds, but the 2NT bid in the second auction shows diamonds and hearts.

|
pg| ***** 161 ***** |


at|The Michaels cuebid convention is a little bit more complicated:

|cs|1|at|^b{ |ia|  1d!2d|at| } ^o{ |ia|  1s!2s|at| }

|
