cs|2|at|^-{ A direct cuebid of an opponent's minor suit opening bid 
 describes a hand with at least 5-5 in the major suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 163 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ A direct cuebid of an opponent's major suit opening bid describes a hand with 
 at least 5 cards in the unbid major and at least 5 cards in one of the minors. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 164 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|At|Having the right distribution to use a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall is only part of the story. Here is a rough estimation of the minimum point count required to use these conventions, but recall that judgment is a better guide than point count in these situations:

|
pg| ***** 165 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In most cases, 10 or more total points are required to use one of these conventions, but a 
 Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening bid can be made with as few as 8 total points. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 166 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ The Michaels cuebid and the Unusual notrump have no upper limit in terms of strength. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 167 ***** |


at|What are you supposed to do when your partner makes a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall? Of course, the answer depends on the cards that you were dealt:

|
pg| ***** 168 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ When responding to one of these conventions, you should bid one of your partner's suits. 
 Bid your longer of these suits and bid the lower ranking of these suits if you have equal length. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 169 ***** |


at|There is one time when the partner of a player who used Michaels will not know exactly which of the 2 suits his partner was dealt. In this case, if he wants to find out, there is a way for him to do so:

|
pg| ***** 170 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Bid 2NT in response to a Michaels cuebid of a major suit 
 opening bid to ask your partner to bid his long minor suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 171 ***** |


at|As we have seen, there are times when it is appropriate to jump in one of your partner's long suits in response to a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall. The factors to be considered when deciding whether or not you should jump will be reviewed soon.|
pg| ***** 172 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|Just because you have the appropriate strength and distribution to make a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall, it does not follow that you should actually do so. You will do better with some of these hands if you pass and on others you will do better if you overcall in one of your long suits. Here are some factors to think about when you are faced with a hand that is marginal for either a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall:

|
pg| ***** 173 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ If most of your high cards are in your long suits, your hand is more suitable for these bids. 
 If most of your high cards are in your short suits, you should consider some other action. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 174 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ If you are vulnerable you should be less aggressive in using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 175 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{If the opponents are vulnerable you should be more aggressive in using these conventions.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 176 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Having strong spot cards in your long suits is a plus factor for using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 177 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ A serious disparity in the quality of your 2 suits is a minus factor for using these conventions. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 178 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In deciding between making an overcall and using Michaels or the unusual notrump, 
 consider the implications of the overcall as far as your second 5-card suit is concerned. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 179 ***** |


cs|1|At|^-{ The more distribution you have, the more you should strive to bid something! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 180 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Some hands with unequal length in the long suits should overcall instead of using Michaels 
 or the Unusual notrump as these conventions could lead to a contract in the wrong suit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 181 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|At|Instead of trying to memorize the list on the previous page as guidelines to use every time you are faced with a decision as to whether or not you should make a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall, it is more practical to keep in mind the primary purpose of using these 
conventions:
|n#|9|
pg| ***** 182 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ These conventions tell your partner that you think it might be a 
 good idea to play in a contract with one of your long suits as trump. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 183 ***** |


at|Furthermore, remember that a good contract is not always a contract that succeeds. Sometimes a partnership can do well by playing in a contract that fails. As long as the other partnership could have succeeded in a contract of their own, a failing contract can be a good sacrifice.
|n#|9|
pg| ***** 184 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Becoming familiar with how bridge is scored will help you to judge well in sacrifice situations. 
 One of the appendices of this program contains a summary of how the scoring works in bridge. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 185 ***** |


at|What if your partner uses a 2-suited overcall and the next player does not pass?
|n#|9|
pg| ***** 186 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ If your partner's Michaels cuebid or Unusual notrump overcall is doubled, 
 it is usually best to make the same bid you would have made without the double. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 187 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Passing the double of a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual notrump overcall is a 
 request for your partner to bid the longer and stronger of the 2 suits that he has shown. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 188 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ If your partner makes a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual notrump overcall and the next 
 hand makes any bid, you should usually pass unless you know that your side has a good fit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 189 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3
There are 2 main advantages to using Michaels cuebids and Unusual notrump overcalls:

|
pg| ***** 190 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ 1. These conventions tell your partner a lot about the nature of your hand in a single bid. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 191 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ 2. If you try overcalling in one of your long suits with the hope of bidding your 
 other long suit later in the auction, it is possible that "later" will never come! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 192 ***** |


at|There are also 2 main disadvantages to using these conventions:

|
pg| ***** 193 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ 1. These conventions force your partner to bid one of your long suits at a fairly high 
 level. Sometimes your partner will not have a good fit for either one of your suits. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 194 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{2. These conventions tell your opponents a lot about the nature of your hand in a single bid.}
^-
|
pg| ***** 195 ***** |


at|In the judgment of the people who designed the SAYC bidding system (as well as that of most of the leading bridge players and theorists in the world), the advantages of using Michaels cuebids and the Unusual notrump outweigh the disadvantages. This is particularly true if you are able to use good judgment as to when these conventions should be used.

|
pg| ***** 196 ***** |


cs|2|At|^-{ When bridge players learn a new convention their natural tendency is to try to use
 it as often as possible. Conventions do not work very well when they are abused! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 197 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Don't make the mistake of using a convention just because you can! }
^-
|
pg| ***** 198 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|
at|Figuring out the best suit to bid when your partner has made a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall is not difficult. Figuring out the right level at which to bid that suit is more complicated and is much more about judgment than it is about point count:
|n#|9|
pg| ***** 199 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ While point count is a valuable tool in many bidding situations, the accuracy of point count 
 tends to break down in competitive auctions, especially when both partnerships have a fit. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 200 ***** |


at|Here are some factors to consider when your partner uses a 2-suited overcall and you are thinking of bidding one of his suits at a higher level than the one at which he forced you to bid:
|n#|9|
pg| ***** 201 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ In these auctions the degree of the fit that you have for your partner and the specific high 
 cards that your hand contains is much more important than your number of total points. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 202 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ The more cards you have in your partner's long suits, the better your hand is. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 203 ***** |


cs|3|at|^-{ Any high cards that you have in your partner's long suits are likely to be valuable. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 204 ***** |


cs|2|at|^-{ Aces in your partner's short suits are good cards to hold (but not as good as Aces in his 
 long suits). Kings, Queens, and Jacks in your partner's short suits are often worthless. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 205 ***** |


cs|4|at|^-{ Try to picture typical hands that your partner could have for his bidding 
 and think about how both partnerships rate to fare in various contracts. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 206 ***** |


cs|1|at|^-{ Consider the vulnerability and the number of points each partnership will score
 in various contracts when you are faced with a competitive bidding decision. }
^-
|
pg| ***** 207 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|n#|5|at|In each of the following exercises, East opens the bidding. You are sitting South and you have to decide if you would pass, overcall, or use a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall.

|
pg| ***** 208 ***** |


md||ha||mb|1d?|ht|d|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|ps7hkq985ckqjt6dk3|at|} |cs|1|ht|e|at|^O{ |ia|  1d?|at| }


|hf|k|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^2n|

cs|1|ht|e|at|^O{ |ia|  1d!2n|at| }


|n#|5|At|Make an Unusual 2NT overcall. This bid shows at least 5 cards in both of the 2 lowest ranking unbid suits. That's clubs and hearts given East's 1@D opening bid. This hand has sound values for an Unusual notrump and 2 strong 5-card suits. What more could you ask for?

|
pg| ***** 210 ***** |


md||ha||mb|1c|ht|n|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|psj8652hajt4daca98|at|} |cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1c?|at| }


|hf|v|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^1s|
cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1c!1s|at| }


|n#|5|at|Overcall 1@S. Your 5-card spade suit is weak, but your hand is sufficiently strong to warrant some kind of action. |
pg| ***** 212 ***** |


at|All of the alternatives have more serious flaws. This hand contains only 4 hearts and, although your hearts are strong, your partner would expect you to have at least 5 of them if you made a Michaels cuebid. |
pg| ***** 213 ***** |


at|^^^^A takeout double, with only 1 card in diamonds, is even more unappealing. |
pg| ***** 214 ***** |


at|Overcalling with a weak 5-card suit should be avoided if possible, but misleading your partner about the distribution of your hand is a more serious transgression! |
pg| ***** 215 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|
md||ha||mb|1h?|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|psqt642h7dkj762ct3|at|} |cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1h?|at| }


|hf|i|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^p|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1h!p|at| }


|n#|5|at|You should pass even though you have the right distribution to make a Michaels cuebid of 2@H. |
pg| ***** 217 ***** |


at|This hand has only 6 HCP. |
pg| ***** 218 ***** |


at|Even when you include 2 long suit points for the 2 5-card suits, you get only 8 total points. Your partner would normally expect you to have at least 10 HCP to make a Michaels cuebid of a major suit opening. Using Michaels with this hand is asking for trouble!

|
pg| ***** 219 ***** |


md||ha||mb|1s|ht|n|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|pskhaqdt9543cq6542|at|} |cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1s?|at| }


|hf|v|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^p|
cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1s!p|at| }


|n#|5|At|Pass again even though your distribution and strength make this hand appropriate for an Unusual 2NT overcall. |
pg| ***** 221 ***** |


at|Most of the high card strength in this hand is in its short suits (the majors) and that should be taken as a warning sign that an Unusual 2NT overcall should be rejected. This hand is more suitable for defense |
pg| ***** 222 ***** |


at|than it is for playing in a contract with one of the minor suits as 
trump. As for the thought of overcalling in one of the minors, it is best to get that out of your head! A 2-level overcall on a weak 5-card suit is something that should be avoided if there is any reasonable alternative. Passing certainly qualifies as a reasonable alternative with this hand.|
pg| ***** 223 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|
md||ha||mb|1c?|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|pskt976hqt9843d6c4|at|} |cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1c?|at| }


|hf|i|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^2c|

cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1c!2c|at| }


|n#|5|At|Make a Michaels cuebid of 2@C to show both majors. |
pg| ***** 225 ***** |


at|This hand has only 5 HCP, |
pg| ***** 226 ***** |


at|but 3 long suit points should be counted (1 for the 5-card spade suit and 2 for the 6-card heart suit). 8 total points is enough for a Michaels cuebid of a minor suit opening. Another plus factor is that this hand has strong spot cards in its long suits. Finally, this hand has the "right" 6-card suit as North will bid hearts if he has equal length in the majors. All of these signs point to using Michaels.

|
pg| ***** 227 ***** |


md||ha||mb|1d|ht|n|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|psaqj83hj5d9caqj98|at|} |cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1d?|at| }


|hf|v|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^1s|
cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1d!1s|at| }


|n#|5|
at|You should overcall 1@S |
pg| ***** 229 ***** |


at|because you have the wrong suits for either a Michaels cuebid or an Unusual 2NT overcall. Michaels would show hearts and spades while an Unusual notrump would show hearts and clubs. This hand contains spades and clubs and, in the SAYC bidding system, there is no way to show both of these suits with a single bid after a 1@D opening by the opponents. Show your spades now and hope to have a convenient chance to show your clubs later in the auction. This hand is ideal for a 2-suited overcall, but there is no 2-suited overcall available to show these particular 2 suits.
|
pg| ***** 230 ***** |


nt|^b@2^z@3|
md||ha||mb|1h?|ht|b|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|ph8cakqt87dakjt94|at|} |cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1h?|at| }


|hf|i|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^2n|
cs|1|ht|c|at|^O{ |ia|  1h!2n|at| }


|n#|5|at|Overcall with an Unusual 2NT to show both minors. It is rare to have a hand that is this powerful, especially when one of the opponents has opened the bidding. Fortunately, there is no upper limit in terms of strength for an Unusual 2NT overcall (or a Michaels cuebid for that matter). This particular hand is so strong that it would not be unreasonable to raise your partner's expected 3@C or 3@D reply all the way to slam!

|
pg| ***** 232 ***** |


md||ha||mb|1s|ht|n|cs|3|at|^C {|ih|phakqt64dq8752c63|at|} |cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1s?|at| }


|hf|v|cq|4|lb|*BWhat call would you make?^^2h|
cs|1|ht|o|at|^O{ |ia|  1s!2h|at| }


|n#|5|at|Overcall 2@H |
pg| ***** 234 ***** |


at|even though you have a Michaels cuebid available to show hearts and one of the minors. The problem with using Michaels with this hand is that your hearts are not only much stronger than your diamonds, they are also longer. On top of that, hearts is a major suit and diamonds is a lowly minor. If you made a Michaels cuebid with this hand, you would sometimes end up in diamonds when you belonged in hearts. |
pg| ***** 235 ***** |


at|^^
A 2@H overcall will increase the partnership's chances of ending up in the right trump suit. |
